description: When DC bought Charlton, they did not acquire Thunderbunny, because he was owned by creator Martin L. Greim. Greim took Thunderbunny to Archie's revived Red Circle imprint, where he received this one-shot, an appearance in Pep Comics #393 two months later, and an appearance in Blue Ribbon Comics #13 seven months later. After this brief stay with Red Circle, Greim would move on to Warp Graphics, where the Thunderbunny title would enjoy a 12 issue run, from 1985 to 1987.
name: Thunderbunny

description:
One of the earliest full colour British weekly comics, The Rainbow debuted on the week of 14th February 1914. A "nursery comic" aimed at younger readers, the front cover starred the Bruin Boys, a group of anthropomorphic animals staying at Mrs. Bruin's boarding school, who had previously appeared in magazine and newspaper supplements. Other strips included "Bobby", "Bonnie Bluebell", "The funny adventures of the Brownie Boys", "The Dolliwogs' Dollshouse", "Full Speed Ahead", "The Island of Wonders", "Ken the Pilot Boy", "Marzipan the Magician", "The Adventures of Marmaduke and Montague, The Merry Mice", "Mops and Co. - The Chums of the Lower Third", "Mrs Tabby and her Tibbies", "On Holiday Farm", "Our Jolly Dolli-Wogs", "Policeman Pete", "Pride of the Ranch", "The Rainbow Pearl", "Sam the Skipper and his little son Jack", "Sing Hi and Sing Lo - The Chinese Twins", "Sonny Day", "Susie Sunshine and her Pretty Pet Poms", "Tommy and His Trains", "The Two Pickles" and "The Wonderful Wagtails".

The leader of the Bruin Boys, Tiger Tim, gained his own title in 1919, but nevertheless continued to appear in The Rainbow. The title lasted for 42 years, finally ceasing publication after 1898 issues on 28th April 1956. Tiger Tim survived The Rainbow's end, transferring to Jack and Jill.
name: Rainbow

description:
Launched on 25th October 1975, Mickey Mouse was a weekly IPC title publishing licensed Disney-related strips for the British market. As well as strips about Disney's various characters derived from cartoon shorts, such as Mickey Mouse himself, the comic also printed serialised adaptations of Disney movies, be they cartoons (e.g. Cinderella or Aristocats), live action (e.g. Candleshoe or Herbie Goes to Monte Carlo), or mixed (e.g. Pete's Dragon), many reprinted from Gold Key's Walt Disney Showcase.

Throughout its run (of at least six years), Mickey Mouse absorbed some of its sister IPC/Disney titles, temporarily modifying its title to reference these mergers, becoming in turn, Mickey Mouse and Donald Duck with #14, back to just Mickey Mouse with #47, Mickey Mouse in Disneyland with #57, Mickey Mouse and Disney Time with #88, reverting to just Mickey Mouse with #116, and ultimately becoming Mickey Magazine with #264. The title came to an end with #280, dated 28th March 1981.
name: Mickey Mouse

description: The original Evangeline series from then married couple Chuck Dixon and Judith Hunt lasted for two issues at Comico before an internal struggle over ownership of the title resulted in the creators pulling Evangline from Comico. It was picked up two years later by David M. Singer's short lived Lodestone Publications before finally finding a more long term home with First Comics in 1987.
name: Evangeline
